Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Boil a #pot{} of @water{to taste}(salted) for the noodles.

Trim and chop the @aubergine{1}(trimmed and chopped into 2cm chunks).

Toss with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} on a lined #baking tray{}.

Roast on the top shelf of the oven for ~{20-25%minutes}.

When the water is boiling, add the @egg noodles{150%grams}.

Cook until softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and return to the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and toss to prevent sticking.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1}(halved and sliced into thin strips) and discard the core and seeds.

Zest and quarter the @lime{1}(zested and quartered).

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed and chopped widthways into quarters) then chop widthways into quarters.

Place a pan over medium-high heat (without oil).

Once the pan is hot, fry the pepper and pak choi until starting to soften, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the @dried chilli flakes{1%sachet} (use less if you don't like spice), lime zest and garlic.

Fry until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add @water{75%ml}, the juice of two lime wedges (double both for 4p), @teriyaki sauce{1%sachet} and @soy sauce{2%sachets} to the pan.

Stir together and bring to the boil.

Add a splash of water to loosen the sauce if needed. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Toss the noodles in the sauce until coated and warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Divide the noodles between #bowls{}.

Top with the tender roasted aubergine.

Scatter over the @peanuts{20%grams}.

Serve remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over.

> The wonderful thing about these garlic noodles is that you can customise them to suit your individual taste. If you're a fan of heat, add plenty of chilli flakes for extra bite. If you like things on the milder side, simply be more reserved with your chilli flake shake!